06.28.11 
Executive Profile: William Y. Tauscher, Chairman and CEO, Blackhawk Network (June 2011)






June 2011


Send to a Friend | Request Reprint | Printable View | Comments |  |




By Loraine DeBonis, Editor-in-Chief
When William (Bill) Y. Tauscher was an undergraduate at Yale, he negotiated with local merchants to create a discount card for students. Decades later, the Yale discount program still is going strong, and Tauscher is still working with retailers—now as chairman and CEO of Blackhawk Network.
“That began my entrepreneurial career … There’s nothing greater than entrepreneurialism,” says Tauscher, who has spent his career building companies, making them more profitable and taking some of them public. “Business makes the world go ’round,” he adds, “and I like very much being able to play a significant role in providing the direction and in building a team.”




In His Own Words
In five years prepaid will be “morphing in ways we do not understand today, other than knowing that the digital revolution will be the major force for change.”
The prepaid industry must “make sure it’s always answering a consumer need in everything it does to keep growing.”
Mobile payments “will be a battle fundamentally to own a digitized wallet that can provide an enhanced consumer shopping experience.”
The most exciting part of my job is “personally engaging with the business partners that make up our network.”
If I’m not in the office, “I’m spending time with family or exercising.”




Tauscher started his professional career at IBM in the retail and distribution division, but since the age of 28 has been his own boss. He has acquired and grown several private and public companies, including Foxmeyer, Vertical Communications, Coast America (acquired by True Value) and Vanstar Corporation. He also served as managing member of the TauscherGroup, a company that invests and assists in the management of enterprises. And, he continues to sit on the board of several companies. 
Moving toward Autonomy
Tauscher took the reins as CEO of Blackhawk in August of 2010, although he began serving as executive chairman in 2009, coming in a few days a week and working with then-CEO Don Kingsborough on moving the company toward independence.
“I’ve helped several private companies substantially grow and have taken four companies public. This was a role I was well-suited for,” he says. Tauscher could not give details about a possible Blackhawk spinoff from parent Safeway, although it’s something Safeway CEO Steven A. Burd has been open about in earnings calls. But Tauscher did say the company has been making investments to strengthen its independence. “All of our processing platforms are now our own, we have our own duplexed data centers with a high-availability setup. We have our own financials and our own audits,” he explains. “Those things are important for this business, which is very different from the grocery retail business.”
When he talks about Blackhawk’s future and that of the prepaid industry, Tauscher becomes animated. “We view our focus to be in sync with the hot and growing areas,” he says. Although Blackhawk’s PayPower products are in the spotlight-stealing general purpose reloadable (GPR) segment, he begins by talking about the company’s explosive growth in gift. “We have to start with our gift card business. It’s growing even faster than some of the market leaders in the GPR space,” he notes. The strong double-digit growth is largely coming from same-store sales, although Blackhawk continues to add new locations as well. “We’re continuing to expand, and our retailers are giving more floor space to gift cards and we’re working with them to increase their promotional activity. “We’re spending significant marketing dollars and have proven these expansions are profitable,” he says.
In addition, Tauscher stresses the importance of execution and “getting back to basics.” “In a business like ours, the basics of in-store merchandising, marketing and promotion cannot be understated.”
It’s that focus that is forging Blackhawk’s presence overseas as well, where the company is achieving three times the growth of its domestic business.
Another growth area Tauscher has his eye on is prepaid wireless minutes and phones. “One in five wireless phones is now a prepaid program with no contract,” he says. “This is the market that’s getting all the growth, and it’s predicted to move up to one in three.” As such, Blackhawk is stepping up its efforts in the prepaid wireless arena and providing large destination displays with a broad handset offering in many of its partner locations.
Midwestern Roots
Tauscher attributes his business acumen to being a pragmatist with an analytical mind, something he inherited from his parents. His dad worked for Caterpillar for years and his mother was a school teacher. Both prized logic.
The family—Tauscher has two brothers—moved around a lot. Tauscher was born in Washington, D.C., but didn’t stay long. And although he lived as far west as Montana, Tauscher claims the Midwest as his home. He spent his high school years in Peoria, Ill., and was the first from his public high school to go to an Ivy League college.
Today, Tauscher makes his home in northern California with his wife, who runs two businesses they own, including a consumer goods company and a gym. He has five children—two business owners in their early 30s who live in Dallas, one who just graduated college and two still in college.
When asked about his career, Tauscher says he’s known since age 5 that he wanted to be a CEO.
“My background has been in retail distribution and technology, but at the end of the day, it’s all about execution,” he notes. “If you think about the fundamentals of prepaid—we often get caught up in the product, its features and its functions—how you acquire customers, how you take care of those customers, who your partners are and how you manage your whole online presence, those are the things that determine the success of anybody in prepaid.
“You can have a great strategy, but what wins in business is out-executing your competitors.”
  |
   


 



