http://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/matier-ross/article/Tauscher-Filing-for-What-Promises-to-Be-a-Messy-3329212.php



Tauscher Filing for What Promises to Be a Messy Divorce


Phillip Matier, Andrew Ross


        Published 4:00 am, Wednesday, March 10, 1999
    
































































1999-03-10 04:00:00 PDT CONTRA COSTA -- Political life has taken its toll on more than a few Washington marriages, but those in the know say that wasn't the case with Representative Ellen Tauscher of Contra Costa County, who has stunned supporters by filing for divorce from her husband of seven years, multimillionaire William Tauscher. 
"This is not a product of her going to Washington," insists one friend of Tauscher. 
What is publicly known is that William Tauscher has admitted having an affair -- and there apparently were signs that not all was well in paradise even before his Democratic wife unseated Republican Bill Baker back in 1996. 



Latest news videos




 
"I'm not surprised in the least," said the source we spoke to. "There were indications that this marital trouble was going on back then." 
Still, William Tauscher, a Republican, was regularly seen at his wife's side throughout the campaign, and he contributed $1.6 million to her winning effort. 
And from the looks of things, his money apparently played a big role in the couple's lifestyle as well -- which included a Washington townhouse on embassy row valued at $1.7 million and a home in the Tassajara Valley, valued at $2.2 million. 
As Tauscher said of her husband in her divorce papers: "Bill has always insisted that we 'live large.' He always ensured that we traveled first-class, stayed in five-star hotels, stayed in suites rather than just regular rooms, ordered caviar at restaurants rather than regular appetizers, drank Crystal, not just ordinary champagne, and paid the tab at each and every meal regardless of who we were with or how many people were dining with us." 
(William Tauscher said their lifestyle was "established mutually." He also corrected his wife on another detail: He drank Dom Perignon, not Crystal.) 
The messy divorce is not only a personal embarrassment for Tauscher, but also a potential political liability if details of the split are dragged out until the next election cycle. 
However, few details of the split are spared in divorce papers. 
The couple's descent from Cloud Nine began in November 1997 when Ellen Tauscher visited the Atlanta home where her husband stayed on business for his computer company, Vanstar, and found a card from one of her husband's female employees. 
She also found a photograph of hubby and the other woman at New York's famous Rainbow Room, where the Tauschers themselves were married July 15, 1989. 
Tauscher said that when she pressed her husband about the photo, he admitted he was having an affair. 
Tauscher said she failed to persuade her husband to stick with counseling to save the marriage -- and hence the divorce. 
Tauscher now wants to depose the other woman to find out whether her husband was funneling a significant amount of the family income into gifts and entertainment for his girlfriend. 
Tauscher, a former stockbroker, claims she knew little of the couple's financial affairs, including her husband's assertion that their family bookkeeper had embezzled millions from them. 
Tauscher, who earns $135,000 a year as a member of Congress, is asking for at least $30,000 a month in spousal support and support for the couple's daughter. 
Her attorney, Robert Nachshin of Los Angeles (who also represented Giants slugger Barry Bonds in his recent divorce), said the case is so complicated that documents alone could fill an entire room. 
In fact, lawyers in the case have agreed to set up two identical "data rooms," one in Northern California and one in Southern California. 
So far, Ken Starr has stayed out of it all -- but now that he has so much time on his hands, who knows? 
 BATTER UP:The Andy Dolich, Joe Morgan and George Zimmer group looking to buy the Oakland A's has added some financial and marketing muscle to its prospective ownership team. 
Among the new marque players, whose names are being submitted to Major League Baseball as part of a possible bid: 
-- Robert Piccinini, chairman and majority shareholder of the Modesto-based Save Mart grocery chain, which operates 98 stores and boasts more than $1 billion in annual sales. 
-- Jeff Goodby, the San Francisco advertising ace who has given us such memorable TV moments as "Got Milk?", the Budweiser talking toads and the A's "Billy Ball" ads a few years back. 
Sources say Piccinini would probably be a major investor (in the $15 million to $20 million range) but not the only one -- other names may soon surface. 
By the way, April 21 is the drop- dead date for any potential bidders to step forward and meet the present owners $122 million asking price for the A's. If that does not happen, the owners have the option to move the team. 
 MR. JOE:We all know Joe DiMaggio was tough to approach for an autograph -- but here's a story about what happened when someone refused to sign one for him. 
It was back in 1994 when Japanese Emperor Akihito and his wife were in town for a black-tie dinner at the Asian Art Museum in Golden Gate Park. 
An avid baseball fan, the emperor went out of his way to have both DiMaggio and Willie Mays invited. 
As former protocol chief Richard Goldman recalls, DiMaggio said "yes," even after being told that he would have to pay his own way here from Florida, where he was living in retirement. 
On the night of the dinner, DiMaggio showed up along with his granddaughter and a baseball he hoped the emperor would sign. 
Then DiMaggio learned that the emperor didn't sign anything. 
Unruffled, DiMaggio and Mays signed the ball themselves and presented it to the emperor. 
"The emperor cupped his hands, his eyes lit up, and he immediately took it over to the empress to show," Goldman recalled. "It was probably the most important gift he got on his whole tour of the United States." 
 














